00:07:15.449 --> 00:07:18.029
So here's the simplest circuit
in the world.

00:07:18.029 --> 00:07:20.189
You have an emf.
 

00:07:20.189 --> 00:07:24.879
There is a resistor and it
comes right back.

00:07:24.879 --> 00:07:27.639
You want to know what current
is flowing in the circuit.

00:07:27.639 --> 00:07:30.154
So the logic,
there are two equations you

00:07:30.154 --> 00:07:30.910
write now.
 

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:34.290
One equation is,
if you start at any point on

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:38.899
the circuit and you go around a
path and you come back to the

00:07:38.899 --> 00:07:41.810
same point,
the change in voltage should be

00:07:41.810 --> 00:07:43.959
zero,
because voltage is like height.

00:07:43.959 --> 00:07:46.740
You can go anywhere you want
and you can come back,

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:49.519
then the change in height
should add up to zero.

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:52.382
If you want,
sum of all the change in

00:07:52.382 --> 00:07:56.040
voltage should be zero around a
closed loop.

00:07:56.040 --> 00:08:00.930
Second thing is,
current is conserved.

00:08:00.930 --> 00:08:02.430
These are the only equations
you need.

00:08:02.430 --> 00:08:03.790
Current doesn't disappear.
 

00:08:03.790 --> 00:08:05.040
It's uniform here.
 

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:09.024
So current I comes here,
drops through the resistor and

00:08:09.024 --> 00:08:11.240
comes out of the other side.
 

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:13.439
So I'm going to write the
following equation.

00:08:13.439 --> 00:08:16.670
I'm going to start at this
point and keep track of all the

00:08:16.670 --> 00:08:17.860
changes in voltage.
 

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:21.629
First when I go around this
battery, I told you many times,

00:08:21.629 --> 00:08:24.620
the change in voltage will be
